# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: beautifulsoup-parsing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/beautiful-soup-html-parser] Beautiful Soup was started in 2004 by Leonard Richardson.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/beautiful-soup-html-parser] It takes its name from the poem *Beautiful Soup* from Alice's Adventures in Wonderland and is a reference to the term "tag soup" meaning poorly-structured HTML code.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/beautiful-soup-html-parser] Richardson continues to contribute to the project, which is additionally supported by paid open-source maintainers from the company Tidelift.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/beautiful-soup-html-parser] Beautiful Soup 3 was the official release line of Beautiful Soup from May 2006 to March 2012.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/beautiful-soup-html-parser] The current release is Beautiful Soup 4.x.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/beautiful-soup-html-parser] In 2021, Python 2.7 support was retired and the release 4.9.3 was the last to support Python 2.7.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/beautiful-soup-html-parser] Beautiful Soup represents parsed data as a tree which can be searched and iterated over with ordinary Python loops.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/beautiful-soup-html-parser] The example below uses the Python standard library's urllib to load Wikipedia's main page, then uses Beautiful Soup to parse the document and search for all links within.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/beautiful-soup-html-parser] Another example is using the Python requests library to get divs on a URL.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] CSS is designed to enable the separation of content and presentation, including layout, colors, and fonts.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] Separation of formatting and content also makes it feasible to present the same markup page in different styles for different rendering methods, such as on-screen, in print, by voice (via speech-based browser or screen reader), and on Braille-based tactile devices.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] CSS also has rules for alternative formatting if the content is accessed on a mobile device.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] The name *cascading* comes from the specified priority scheme to determine which declaration applies if more than one declaration of a property match a particular element.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] This cascading priority scheme is predictable.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] The CSS specifications are maintained by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] Internet media type (MIME type) `text/css` is registered for use with CSS by RFC 2318 (March 1998).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] The W3C operates a free CSS validation service for CSS documents.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] In addition to HTML, other markup languages support the use of CSS including XHTML, plain XML, SVG, and XUL.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] CSS is also used in the GTK widget toolkit.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] CSS has a simple syntax and uses a number of English keywords to specify the names of various style properties.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] A style sheet consists of a list of *rules*.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] Each rule or rule-set consists of one or more *selectors*, and a *declaration block*.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] In CSS, *selectors* declare which part of the markup a style applies to by matching tags and attributes in the markup itself.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] Classes and IDs are case-sensitive, start with letters, and can include alphanumeric characters, hyphens, and underscores.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] A class may apply to any number of instances of any element.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] An ID may only be applied to a single element.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] One example of a widely used pseudo-class is `:hover`, which identifies content only when the user "points to" the visible element, usually by holding the mouse cursor over it.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] It is appended to a selector as in `a:hover` or `#elementid:hover`.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] A pseudo-class classifies document elements, such as `:link` or `:visited`, whereas a *pseudo-element* makes a selection that may consist of partial elements, such as `::first-line` or `::first-letter`.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] Note the distinction between the double-colon notation used for pseudo-elements and the single-colon notation used for pseudo-classes.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] Multiple simple selectors may be joined using combinators to specify elements by location, element type, id, class, or any combination thereof.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] The order of the selectors is important.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] For example, `div .myClass {color: red;}` applies to all elements of class myClass that are inside div elements, whereas `.myClass div {color: red;}` applies to all div elements that are inside elements of class myClass.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] This is not to be confused with concatenated identifiers such as `div.myClass {color: red;}` which applies to div elements of class myClass.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] The following table provides a summary of selector syntax indicating usage and the version of CSS that introduced it.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] A declaration block consists of a pair of braces (`{}`) enclosing a semicolon-separated list of *declarations*.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] Each declaration itself consists of a *property*, a colon (`:`), and a *value*.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] Optional white-space may be around the declaration block, declarations, colons, and semi-colons for readability.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] Properties are specified in the CSS standard.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] Each property has a set of possible values.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] Some properties can affect any type of element, and others apply only to particular groups of elements.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] Values may be keywords, such as "center" or "inherit", or numerical values, such as `200px` (200 pixels), `50vw` (50 percent of the viewport width) or 80% (80 percent of the parent element's width).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] Color values can be specified with keywords (e.g.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] `rgb(255, 0, 0)`), RGBA values that specify both color and alpha transparency (e.g.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] Non-zero numeric values representing linear measures must include a length unit, which is either an alphabetic code or abbreviation, as in `200px` or `50vw`; or a percentage sign, as in `80%`.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] These eight units were a feature of CSS 1 and retained in all subsequent revisions.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] The proposed CSS Values and Units Module Level 3 will, if adopted as a W3C Recommendation, provide seven further length units: `ch`; `Q`; `rem`; `vh`; `vmax`; `vmin`; and `vw`.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] Before CSS, nearly all presentational attributes of HTML documents were contained within the HTML markup.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] That is, all font colors, background styles, element alignments, borders, and sizes had to be explicitly described (often repeatedly) within the HTML.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] CSS lets authors move much of that information to another file, the style sheet, resulting in considerably simpler HTML.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] And additionally, as more and more devices are able to access responsive web pages, different screen sizes and layouts begin to appear.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] Customizing a website for each device size is costly and increasingly difficult.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] The modular nature of CSS means that styles can be reused in different parts of a site or even across sites, promoting consistency and efficiency.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] For example, headings (`h1` elements), sub-headings (`h2`), sub-sub-headings (`h3`), etc., are defined structurally using HTML.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] In print and on the screen, choice of font, size, color and emphasis for these elements is *presentational*.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] Before CSS, document authors who wanted to assign such typographic characteristics to, say, all `h2` headings had to repeat HTML presentational markup for each occurrence of that heading type.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] This made documents more complex, larger, and more error-prone and difficult to maintain.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] CSS allows the separation of presentation from structure.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] CSS can define color, font, text alignment, size, borders, spacing, layout and many other typographic characteristics, and can do so independently for on-screen and printed views.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] CSS also defines non-visual styles, such as reading speed and emphasis for aural text readers.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] The W3C has now deprecated the use of all presentational HTML markup.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] The advantages of this may not be immediately clear but the power of CSS becomes more apparent when the style properties are placed in an internal style element or, even better, an external CSS file.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] All `h1` elements in the document will then automatically become red without requiring any explicit code.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] rather than by laboriously going through the document and changing the color for each individual `h1` element.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/css-selector] This further decouples the styling from the HTML document and makes it possible to restyle multiple documents by simply editing a shared external CSS file.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] The **Document Object Model** (**DOM**) is a cross-platform and language-independent API that treats an HTML or XML document as a tree structure wherein each node is an object representing a part of the document.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] The DOM represents a document with a logical tree.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Each branch of the tree ends in a node, and each node contains objects.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] DOM methods allow programmatic access to the tree; with them one can change the structure, style or content of a document.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Nodes can have event handlers (also known as event listeners) attached to them.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Once an event is triggered, the event handlers get executed.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] The principal standardization of the DOM was handled by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), which last developed a recommendation in 2004.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] WHATWG took over the development of the standard, publishing it as a living document.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] The W3C now publishes stable snapshots of the WHATWG standard.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] JavaScript was released by Netscape Communications in 1995 within Netscape Navigator 2.0.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Netscape's competitor, Microsoft, released Internet Explorer 3.0 the following year with a reimplementation of JavaScript called JScript.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] JavaScript and JScript let web developers create web pages with client-side interactivity.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Legacy DOM was limited in the kinds of elements that could be accessed.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Form, link and image elements could be referenced with a hierarchical name that began with the root document object.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] A hierarchical name could make use of either the names or the sequential index of the traversed elements.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] For example, a form input element could be accessed as either `document.myForm.myInput` or `document.forms[0].elements[0]`.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] The Legacy DOM enabled client-side form validation and simple interface interactivity like creating tooltips.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] In 1997, Netscape and Microsoft released version 4.0 of Netscape Navigator and Internet Explorer respectively, adding support for Dynamic HTML (DHTML) functionality enabling changes to a loaded HTML document.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] DHTML required extensions to the rudimentary document object that was available in the Legacy DOM implementations.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Although the Legacy DOM implementations were largely compatible since JScript was based on JavaScript, the DHTML DOM extensions were developed in parallel by each browser maker and remained incompatible.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] These versions of the DOM became known as the "Intermediate DOM".
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] After the standardization of ECMAScript, the W3C DOM Working Group began drafting a standard DOM specification.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] The completed specification, known as "DOM Level 1", became a W3C Recommendation in late 1998.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] By 2005, large parts of W3C DOM were well-supported by common ECMAScript-enabled browsers, including Internet Explorer 6 (from 2001), Opera, Safari and Gecko-based browsers (like Mozilla, Firefox, SeaMonkey and Camino).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] The W3C DOM Working Group published its final recommendation and subsequently disbanded in 2004.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Development efforts migrated to the WHATWG, which continues to maintain a living standard.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] In 2009, the Web Applications group reorganized DOM activities at the W3C.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] In 2013, due to a lack of progress and the impending release of HTML5, the DOM Level 4 specification was reassigned to the HTML Working Group to expedite its completion.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Meanwhile, in 2015, the Web Applications group was disbanded and DOM stewardship passed to the Web Platform group.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Beginning with the publication of DOM Level 4 in 2015, the W3C creates new recommendations based on snapshots of the WHATWG standard.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] To render a document such as a HTML page, most web browsers use an internal model similar to the DOM.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] The nodes of every document are organized in a tree structure, called the *DOM tree*, with the topmost node named as "Document object".
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] When an HTML page is rendered in browsers, the browser downloads the HTML into local memory and automatically parses it to display the page on screen.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] However, the DOM does not necessarily need to be represented as a tree, and some browsers have used other internal models.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] When a web page is loaded, the browser creates a Document Object Model of the page, which is an object oriented representation of an HTML document that acts as an interface between JavaScript and the document itself.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] A Document Object Model (DOM) tree is a hierarchical representation of an HTML or XML document.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] It consists of a root node, which is the document itself, and a series of child nodes that represent the elements, attributes, and text content of the document.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Each node in the tree has a parent node, except for the root node, and can have multiple child nodes.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Elements in an HTML or XML document are represented as nodes in the DOM tree.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Each element node has a tag name and attributes, and can contain other element nodes or text nodes as children.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Text content within an element is represented as a text node in the DOM tree.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Text nodes do not have attributes or child nodes and are therefore always leaf nodes in the tree.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] For example, the text content "My Website" in the title element and "Welcome" in the h1 element are both represented as text nodes.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Attributes of an element are represented as properties of the element node in the DOM tree.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] The DOM tree can be manipulated using JavaScript or other programming languages.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Common tasks include navigating the tree, adding, removing, and modifying nodes, and getting and setting the properties of nodes.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] The DOM API provides a set of methods and properties to perform these operations, such as `getElementById`, `createElement`, `appendChild`, and `innerHTML`.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Another way to create a DOM structure is using the innerHTML property to insert HTML code as a string, creating the elements and children in the process.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Another method is to use a JavaScript library or framework such as jQuery, AngularJS, React, Vue.js, Svelte, etc.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] These libraries provide an efficient way to create, manipulate and interact with the DOM.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] It is also possible to create a DOM structure from an XML or JSON data, using JavaScript methods to parse the data and create the nodes accordingly.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Creating a DOM structure does not necessarily mean that it will be displayed in the web page, it only exists in memory and should be appended to the document body or a specific container to be rendered.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] In summary, creating a DOM structure involves creating individual nodes and organizing them in a hierarchical structure using JavaScript or other programming languages, and it can be done using several methods depending on the use case and the developer's preference.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Because the DOM supports navigation in any direction (e.g., parent and previous sibling) and allows for arbitrary modifications, implementations typically buffer the document.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] However, a DOM need not originate in a serialized document at all, but can be created in place with the DOM API.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] And even before the idea of the DOM originated, there were implementations of equivalent structure with persistent disk representation and rapid access, for example DynaText's model disclosed in and various database approaches.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Web browsers rely on layout engines to parse HTML into a DOM.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Some layout engines, such as Trident/MSHTML, are associated primarily or exclusively with a particular browser, such as Internet Explorer.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] Others, including Blink, WebKit, and Gecko, are shared by a number of browsers, such as Google Chrome, Opera, Safari, and Firefox.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/document-object-model] The different layout engines implement the DOM standards to varying degrees of compliance.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Web browsers receive HTML documents from a web server or from local storage and render the documents into multimedia web pages.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] HTML describes the structure of a web page semantically and originally included cues for its appearance.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] HTML elements are the building blocks of HTML pages.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] With HTML constructs, images and other objects such as interactive forms may be embedded into the rendered page.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] HTML provides a means to create structured documents by denoting structural semantics for text such as headings, paragraphs, lists, links, quotes, and other items.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] HTML elements are delineated by *tags*, written using angle brackets.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Tags such as `<img>` and `<input>` directly introduce content into the page.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Other tags such as `<p>` and its corresponding closing tag `</p>` surround and provide information about document text and may include sub-element tags.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Browsers do not display the HTML tags, but use them to interpret the content of the page.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] HTML can embed programs written in a scripting language such as JavaScript, which affects the behavior and content of web pages.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The inclusion of CSS defines the look and layout of content.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), former maintainer of the HTML and current maintainer of the CSS standards, has encouraged the use of CSS over explicit presentational HTML since 1997.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] A form of HTML, known as HTML5, is used to display video and audio, primarily using the `<canvas>` element, together with JavaScript.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In 1980, the physicist Tim Berners-Lee, a contractor at CERN, proposed and prototyped ENQUIRE, a system for CERN researchers to use and share documents.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In 1989, Berners-Lee wrote a memo proposing an Internet-based hypertext system.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Berners-Lee specified HTML and wrote the browser and server software in late 1990.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] That year, Berners-Lee and CERN data systems engineer Robert Cailliau collaborated on a joint request for funding, but the project was not formally adopted by CERN.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In his personal notes of 1990, Berners-Lee listed "some of the many areas in which hypertext is used"; an encyclopedia is the first entry.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The first publicly available description of HTML was a document called "HTML Tags", first mentioned on the Internet by Tim Berners-Lee in late 1991.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] It describes 18 elements comprising the initial, relatively simple design of HTML.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Except for the hyperlink tag, these were strongly influenced by CERN SGML, an in-house Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML)-based documentation format at CERN.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Eleven of these elements still exist in HTML 4.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] HTML is a markup language that web browsers use to interpret and compose text, images, and other material into visible or audible web pages.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Default characteristics for every item of HTML markup are defined in the browser, and these characteristics can be altered or enhanced by the web page designer's additional use of CSS.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] These formatting commands were derived from the commands used by typesetters to manually format documents.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] However, the SGML concept of generalized markup is based on elements (nested annotated ranges with attributes) rather than merely print effects, with separate structure and markup.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] HTML has been progressively moved in this direction with CSS.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Berners-Lee considered HTML to be an application of SGML.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The draft expired after six months, but was notable for its acknowledgment of the NCSA Mosaic browser's custom tag for embedding in-line images, reflecting the IETF's philosophy of basing standards on successful prototypes.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Similarly, Dave Raggett's competing Internet Draft, "HTML+ (Hypertext Markup Format)", from late 1993, suggested standardizing already-implemented features like tables and fill-out forms.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] After the HTML and HTML+ drafts expired in early 1994, the IETF created an HTML Working Group.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In 1995, this working group completed "HTML 2.0", the first HTML specification intended to be treated as a standard against which future implementations should be based.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Further development under the auspices of the IETF was stalled by competing interests.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Since 1996, the HTML specifications have been maintained, with input from commercial software vendors, by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In 2000, HTML became an international standard (ISO/IEC 15445:2000).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] HTML 4.01 was published in late 1999, with further errata published through 2001.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In 2004, development began on HTML5 in the Web Hypertext Application Technology Working Group (WHATWG), which became a joint deliverable with the W3C in 2008, and was completed and standardized on 28 October 2014.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] It was the first version developed and standardized exclusively by the W3C, as the IETF had closed its HTML Working Group on 12 September 1996.
