[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] On 14 February 2011, the W3C extended the charter of its HTML Working Group with clear milestones for HTML5.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In May 2011, the working group advanced HTML5 to "Last Call", an invitation to communities inside and outside W3C to confirm the technical soundness of the specification.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The W3C developed a comprehensive test suite to achieve broad interoperability for the full specification by 2014, which was the target date for recommendation.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In January 2011, the WHATWG renamed its "HTML5" living standard to "HTML".
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The W3C nevertheless continued its project to release HTML5.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] W3C will continue the HTML5 specification work, focusing on a single definitive standard, which is considered a "snapshot" by WHATWG.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The WHATWG organization will continue its work with HTML5 as a "Living Standard".
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The concept of a living standard is that it is never complete and is always being updated and improved.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] New features can be added but functionality will not be removed.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In December 2012, W3C designated HTML5 as a Candidate Recommendation.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] is "two 100% complete and fully interoperable implementations".
