[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] XHTML is a separate language that began as a reformulation of HTML 4.01 using XML 1.0.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] It is now referred to as *the XML syntax for HTML* and is no longer being developed as a separate standard.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] On 28 May 2019, the W3C announced that WHATWG would be the sole publisher of the HTML and DOM standards.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The W3C and WHATWG had been publishing competing standards since 2012.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] While the W3C standard was identical to the WHATWG in 2007 the standards have since progressively diverged due to different design decisions.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The WHATWG "Living Standard" had been the *de facto* web standard for some time.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The W3C periodically reviews and publishes snapshots of the WHATWG HTML specification as W3C Recommendations.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] HTML markup consists of several key components, including those called *tags* (and their *attributes*), character-based *data types*, *character references* and *entity references*.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] HTML tags most commonly come in pairs like `<h1>` and `</h1>`, although some represent *empty elements* and so are unpaired, for example `<img>`.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The first tag in such a pair is the *start tag*, and the second is the *end tag* (they are also called *opening tags* and *closing tags*).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Another important component is the HTML *document type declaration*, which triggers standards mode rendering.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The text between `<html>` and `</html>` describes the web page, and the text between `<body>` and `</body>` is the visible page content.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The markup text `<title>This is a title</title>` defines the browser page title shown on browser tabs and window titles and the tag `<div>` defines a division of the page used for easy styling.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Between `<head>` and `</head>`, a `<meta>` element can be used to define webpage metadata.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The Document Type Declaration `<!DOCTYPE html>` is for HTML5.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] If a declaration is not included, various browsers will revert to "quirks mode" for rendering.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] HTML documents imply a structure of nested HTML elements.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] These are indicated in the document by HTML *tags*, enclosed in angle brackets.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In the simple, general case, the extent of an element is indicated by a pair of tags: a "start tag" `<p>` and "end tag" `</p>`.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The text content of the element, if any, is placed between these tags.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Tags may also enclose further tag markup between the start and end, including a mixture of tags and text.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] This indicates further (nested) elements, as children of the parent element.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The start tag may also include the element's *attributes* within the tag.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Some elements, such as the line break `<br>` do not permit *any* embedded content, either text or further tags.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] These require only a single empty tag (akin to a start tag) and do not use an end tag.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Many tags, particularly the closing end tag for the very commonly used paragraph element `<p>`, are optional.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] An HTML browser or other agent can infer the closure for the end of an element from the context and the structural rules defined by the HTML standard.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] These rules are complex and not widely understood by most HTML authors.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The general form of an HTML element is therefore: `<tag attribute1="value1" attribute2="value2">''content''</tag>`.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Some HTML elements are defined as *empty elements* and take the form `<tag attribute1="value1" attribute2="value2">`.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Empty elements may enclose no content, for instance, the `<br>` tag or the inline `<img>` tag.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The name of an HTML element is the name used in the tags.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The end tag's name is preceded by a slash character `/`.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] If a tag has no content, an end tag is not allowed.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] If attributes are not mentioned, default values are used in each case.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Header of the HTML document: `<head>...</head>`.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] CSS can substantially change the rendering.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The difference between `<br>` and `<p>` is that `<br>` breaks a line without altering the semantic structure of the page, whereas `<p>` sections the page into paragraphs.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The element `<br>` is an *empty element* in that, although it may have attributes, it can take no content and it must not have an end tag.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The `href` attribute holds the URL address of the link.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Comments can help in the understanding of the markup and do not display in the webpage.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Most of the attributes of an element are name–value pairs, separated by `=` and written within the start tag of an element after the element's name.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The value may be enclosed in single or double quotes, although values consisting of certain characters can be left unquoted in HTML (but not XHTML).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Leaving attribute values unquoted is considered unsafe.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In contrast with name-value pair attributes, there are some attributes that affect the element simply by their presence in the start tag of the element, like the `ismap` attribute for the `img` element.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Most elements take the language-related attribute `dir` to specify text direction, such as with "rtl" for right-to-left text in, for example, Arabic, Persian or Hebrew.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] As of version 4.0, HTML defines a set of 252 character entity references and a set of 1,114,050 numeric character references, both of which allow individual characters to be written via simple markup, rather than literally.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] A literal character and its markup counterpart are considered equivalent and are rendered identically.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The ability to "escape" characters in this way allows for the characters `<` and `&` (when written as `&lt;` and `&amp;`, respectively) to be interpreted as character data, rather than markup.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] For example, a literal `<` normally indicates the start of a tag, and `&` normally indicates the start of a character entity reference or numeric character reference; writing it as `&amp;` or `&#x26;` or `&#38;` allows `&` to be included in the content of an element or in the value of an attribute.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The double-quote character (`"`), when not used to quote an attribute value, must also be escaped as `&quot;` or `&#x22;` or `&#34;` when it appears within the attribute value itself.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Equivalently, the single-quote character (`'`), when not used to quote an attribute value, must also be escaped as `&#x27;` or `&#39;` (or as `&apos;` in HTML5 or XHTML documents) when it appears within the attribute value itself.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] If document authors overlook the need to escape such characters, some browsers can be very forgiving and try to use context to guess their intent.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The result is still invalid markup, which makes the document less accessible to other browsers and to other user agents that may try to parse the document for search and indexing purposes for example.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Escaping also allows for characters that are not easily typed, or that are not available in the document's character encoding, to be represented within the element and attribute content.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Unicode character encodings such as UTF-8 are compatible with all modern browsers and allow direct access to almost all the characters of the world's writing systems.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] HTML defines several data types for element content, such as script data and stylesheet data, and a plethora of types for attribute values, including IDs, names, URIs, numbers, units of length, languages, media descriptors, colors, character encodings, dates and times, and so on.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] All of these data types are specializations of character data.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] HTML documents are required to start with a document type declaration (informally, a "doctype").
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In browsers, the doctype helps to define the rendering mode—particularly whether to use quirks mode.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The original purpose of the doctype was to enable the parsing and validation of HTML documents by SGML tools based on the document type definition (DTD).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The DTD to which the DOCTYPE refers contains a machine-readable grammar specifying the permitted and prohibited content for a document conforming to such a DTD.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Browsers, on the other hand, do not implement HTML as an application of SGML and as consequence do not read the DTD.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] This declaration references the DTD for the "strict" version of HTML 4.01.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] SGML-based validators read the DTD in order to properly parse the document and to perform validation.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In modern browsers, a valid doctype activates standards mode as opposed to quirks mode.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In addition, HTML 4.01 provides Transitional and Frameset DTDs, as explained below.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The transitional type is the most inclusive, incorporating current tags as well as older or "deprecated" tags, with the Strict DTD excluding deprecated tags.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The frameset has all tags necessary to make frames on a page along with the tags included in transitional type.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Semantic HTML is a way of writing HTML that emphasizes the meaning of the encoded information over its presentation (look).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] HTML has included semantic markup from its inception, but has also included presentational markup, such as `<font>`, `<i>`, and `<center>` tags.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] There are also the semantically neutral div and span tags.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Since the late 1990s, when Cascading Style Sheets were beginning to work in most browsers, web authors have been encouraged to avoid the use of presentational HTML markup with a view to the separation of content and presentation.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In a 2001 discussion of the Semantic Web, Tim Berners-Lee and others gave examples of ways in which intelligent software "agents" may one day automatically crawl the web and find, filter, and correlate previously unrelated, published facts for the benefit of human users.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Such agents are not commonplace even now, but some of the ideas of Web 2.0, mashups and price comparison websites may be coming close.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] An important type of web agent that does crawl and read web pages automatically, without prior knowledge of what it might find, is the web crawler or search-engine spider.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] These software agents are dependent on the semantic clarity of web pages they find as they use various techniques and algorithms to read and index millions of web pages a day and provide web users with search facilities without which the World Wide Web's usefulness would be greatly reduced.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Presentational markup tags are deprecated in current HTML and XHTML recommendations.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The majority of presentational features from previous versions of HTML are no longer allowed as they lead to poorer accessibility, higher cost of site maintenance, and larger document sizes.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Good semantic HTML also improves the accessibility of web documents (see also Web Content Accessibility Guidelines).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] For example, when a screen reader or audio browser can correctly ascertain the structure of a document, it will not waste the visually impaired user's time by reading out repeated or irrelevant information when it has been marked up correctly.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] HTML documents can be delivered by the same means as any other computer file.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] However, they are most often delivered either by HTTP from a web server or by email.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The World Wide Web is composed primarily of HTML documents transmitted from web servers to web browsers using the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] However, HTTP is used to serve images, sound, and other content, in addition to HTML.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] To allow the web browser to know how to handle each document it receives, other information is transmitted along with the document.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] This meta data usually includes the MIME type (e.g., text/html or application/xhtml+xml) and the character encoding (see Character encodings in HTML).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In modern browsers, the MIME type that is sent with the HTML document may affect how the document is initially interpreted.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] A document sent with the XHTML MIME type is expected to be well-formed XML; syntax errors may cause the browser to fail to render it.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The same document sent with the HTML MIME type might be displayed successfully since some browsers are more lenient with HTML.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The W3C recommendations state that XHTML 1.0 documents that follow guidelines set forth in the recommendation's Appendix C may be labeled with either MIME Type.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] XHTML 1.1 also states that XHTML 1.1 documents should be labeled with either MIME type.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Most graphical email clients allow the use of a subset of HTML (often ill-defined) to provide formatting and semantic markup not available with plain text.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] This may include typographic information like colored headings, emphasized and quoted text, inline images and diagrams.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Many such clients include both a GUI editor for composing HTML e-mail messages and a rendering engine for displaying them.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Use of HTML in e-mail is criticized by some because of compatibility issues, because it can help disguise phishing attacks, because of accessibility issues for blind or visually impaired people, because it can confuse spam filters and because the message size is larger than plain text.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The most common filename extension for files containing HTML is .html.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] A common abbreviation of this is .htm, which originated because some operating systems limit file extensions to three letters.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] An HTML Application (HTA; file extension .hta) is a Microsoft Windows application that uses HTML and Dynamic HTML in a browser to provide the application's graphical interface.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] A regular HTML file is confined to the security model of the web browser's security, communicating only to web servers and manipulating only web page objects and site cookies.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] An HTA runs as a fully trusted application and therefore has more privileges, like creation/editing/removal of files and Windows Registry entries.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Because they operate outside the browser's security model, HTAs cannot be executed via HTTP, but must be downloaded (just like an EXE file) and executed from local file system.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Since its inception, HTML and its associated protocols gained acceptance relatively quickly.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] However, no clear standards existed in the early years of the language.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Though its creators originally conceived of HTML as a semantic language devoid of presentation details, practical uses pushed many presentational elements and attributes into the language, driven largely by the various browser vendors.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The latest standards surrounding HTML reflect efforts to overcome the sometimes chaotic development of the language and to create a rational foundation for building both meaningful and well-presented documents.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] To return HTML to its role as a semantic language, the W3C has developed style languages such as CSS and XSL to shoulder the burden of presentation.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In conjunction, the HTML specification has slowly reined in the presentational elements.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] There are two axes differentiating various variations of HTML as currently specified: SGML-based HTML versus XML-based HTML (referred to as XHTML) on one axis, and strict versus transitional (loose) versus frameset on the other axis.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] One difference in the latest HTML specifications lies in the distinction between the SGML-based specification and the XML-based specification.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The XML-based specification is usually called XHTML to distinguish it clearly from the more traditional definition.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] However, the root element name continues to be "html" even in the XHTML-specified HTML.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The W3C intended XHTML 1.0 to be identical to HTML 4.01 except where limitations of XML over the more complex SGML require workarounds.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Because XHTML and HTML are closely related, they are sometimes documented in parallel.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In such circumstances, some authors conflate the two names as (X)HTML or X(HTML).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Like HTML 4.01, XHTML 1.0 has three sub-specifications: strict, transitional, and frameset.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Aside from the different opening declarations for a document, the differences between an HTML 4.01 and XHTML 1.0 document—in each of the corresponding DTDs—are largely syntactic.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The underlying syntax of HTML allows many shortcuts that XHTML does not, such as elements with optional opening or closing tags, and even empty elements which must not have an end tag.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] By contrast, XHTML requires all elements to have an opening tag and a closing tag.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] XHTML, however, also introduces a new shortcut: an XHTML tag may be opened and closed within the same tag, by including a slash before the end of the tag like this: `<br/>`.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The introduction of this shorthand, which is not used in the SGML declaration for HTML 4.01, may confuse earlier software unfamiliar with this new convention.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] A fix for this is remove the slash preceding the closing angle bracket, as such: `<br>`.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] To understand the subtle differences between HTML and XHTML, consider the transformation of a valid and well-formed XHTML 1.0 document that adheres to Appendix C (see below) into a valid HTML 4.01 document.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Change the document type declaration from XHTML 1.0 to HTML 4.01.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Ensure that the document's MIME type is set to `text/html`.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] For both HTML and XHTML, this comes from the HTTP `Content-Type` header sent by the server.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Change the XML empty-element syntax to an HTML style empty element (`<br/>` to `<br>`).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Those are the main changes necessary to translate a document from XHTML 1.0 to HTML 4.01.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] To translate from HTML to XHTML would also require the addition of any omitted opening or closing tags.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Whether coding in HTML or XHTML it may just be best to always include the optional tags within an HTML document rather than remembering which tags can be omitted.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] A well-formed XHTML document adheres to all the syntax requirements of XML.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] A valid document adheres to the content specification for XHTML, which describes the document structure.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The W3C recommends several conventions to ensure an easy migration between HTML and XHTML.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] By carefully following the W3C's compatibility guidelines, a user agent should be able to interpret the document equally as HTML or XHTML.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] For documents that are XHTML 1.0 and have been made compatible in this way, the W3C permits them to be served either as HTML (with a `text/html` MIME type), or as XHTML (with an `application/xhtml+xml` or `application/xml` MIME type).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] When delivered as XHTML, browsers should use an XML parser, which adheres strictly to the XML specifications for parsing the document's contents.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] HTML 4 defined three different versions of the language: Strict, Transitional (once called Loose), and Frameset.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The Strict version is intended for new documents and is considered best practice, while the Transitional and Frameset versions were developed to make it easier to transition documents that conformed to older HTML specifications or did not conform to any specification to a version of HTML 4.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The Transitional and Frameset versions allow for presentational markup, which is omitted in the Strict version.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Instead, cascading style sheets are encouraged to improve the presentation of HTML documents.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Because XHTML 1 only defines an XML syntax for the language defined by HTML 4, the same differences apply to XHTML 1 as well.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The Frameset version includes everything in the Transitional version, as well as the `frameset` element (used instead of `body`) and the `frame` element.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In addition to the above transitional differences, the frameset specifications (whether XHTML 1.0 or HTML 4.01) specify a different content model, with `frameset` replacing `body`, that contains either `frame` elements, or optionally `noframes` with a `body`.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] As this list demonstrates, the loose versions of the specification are maintained for legacy support.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] However, contrary to popular misconceptions, the move to XHTML does not imply a removal of this legacy support.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Rather the X in XML stands for extensible and the W3C is modularizing the entire specification and opens it up to independent extensions.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The primary achievement in the move from XHTML 1.0 to XHTML 1.1 is the modularization of the entire specification.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The strict version of HTML is deployed in XHTML 1.1 through a set of modular extensions to the base XHTML 1.1 specification.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Likewise, someone looking for the loose (transitional) or frameset specifications will find similar extended XHTML 1.1 support (much of it is contained in the legacy or frame modules).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Modularization also allows for separate features to develop on their own timetable.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] So for example, XHTML 1.1 will allow quicker migration to emerging XML standards such as MathML (a presentational and semantic math language based on XML) and XForms—a new highly advanced web-form technology to replace the existing HTML forms.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] In summary, the HTML 4 specification primarily reined in all the various HTML implementations into a single clearly written specification based on SGML.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] XHTML 1.0, ported this specification, as is, to the new XML-defined specification.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] Next, XHTML 1.1 takes advantage of the extensible nature of XML and modularizes the whole specification.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] XHTML 2.0 was intended to be the first step in adding new features to the specification in a standards-body-based approach.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The HTML Living Standard, which is developed by WHATWG, is the official version, while W3C HTML5 is no longer separate from WHATWG.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] WYSIWYG editors (*what you see is what you get*), are HTML editors in which the user lays out everything as it is to appear in the HTML document using a graphical user interface (GUI), such as Microsoft FrontPage, often similar to word processors.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The editor renders the document rather than showing the code, so authors do not require extensive knowledge of HTML.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/html] The WYSIWYG editing model has been criticized, primarily because of the low quality of the generated code; there are various developers advocating a change to the WYSIWYM model (*what you see is what you mean*).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Scraping a web page involves fetching it and then extracting data from it.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Fetching is the downloading of a page (which a browser does when a user views a page).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Therefore, web crawling is a main component of web scraping, to fetch pages for later processing.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Having fetched, extraction can take place.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] The content of a page may be parsed, searched and reformatted, and its data copied into a spreadsheet or loaded into a database.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Web scrapers typically take something out of a page, to make use of it for another purpose somewhere else.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] An example would be finding and copying names and telephone numbers, companies and their URLs, or e-mail addresses to a list (contact scraping).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Another example is collecting competitors product prices for marketing purposes, which can involve gathering large-scale pricing datasets from e-commerce websites and analysing them using data science techniques such as trend analysis, predictive modelling, and competitive benchmarking.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Web pages are built using text-based markup languages (HTML and XHTML), and frequently contain a wealth of data in text form.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] However, most web pages are designed for human end-users and not for ease of automated use.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] As a result, specialized tools and software have been developed to facilitate the scraping of web pages.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Web scraping applications include market research, price comparison, content monitoring and artificial intelligence.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Businesses rely on web scraping services to efficiently gather and utilize this data.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Newer forms of web scraping involve monitoring data feeds from web servers.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] For example, JSON is commonly used as a transport mechanism between the client and the web server.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] There are methods that some websites use to prevent web scraping, such as detecting and disallowing bots from crawling (viewing) their pages.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] In response, web scraping systems use techniques involving DOM parsing, computer vision and natural language processing to simulate human-like browsing to enable gathering web page content for offline parsing.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] After the birth of the World Wide Web in 1989, the first web robot, World Wide Web Wanderer, was created in June 1993, which was intended only to measure the size of the web.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] In December 1993, the first crawler-based web search engine, JumpStation, was launched.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] As there were fewer websites available on the web, search engines at that time used to rely on human administrators to collect and format links.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] In comparison, Jump Station was the first WWW search engine to rely on a web robot.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] In 2000, the first Web API and API crawler were created.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] In 2000, Salesforce and eBay launched their own API, with which programmers could access and download some of the data available to the public.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Since then, many websites offer web APIs for people to access their public database.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Data extraction techniques range from manual collection to sophisticated automated systems.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Advanced methods analyze the underlying structure of web pages to transform unstructured content into a machine-readable format.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] These techniques utilize text processing or artificial intelligence, aligning with the technical goals of the Semantic Web.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] The simplest form of web scraping is manual copying and pasting of data from a web page into a text file or spreadsheet.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] This approach requires no technical tools and can be used when automated scraping is blocked by website restrictions or when human judgment is necessary to interpret complex content.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] However, manual scraping is highly inefficient for large datasets, as it is time-consuming, prone to human error, and mentally exhausting.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] For this reason, it is generally considered impractical compared to automated methods, except in cases where automation is not feasible.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] A simple approach to extract information from web pages is to use the UNIX grep command or regular expression-matching facilities of programming languages (for instance Perl or Python), in order to find text matching a specified pattern.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Static and dynamic web pages can be retrieved by posting HTTP requests to the remote web server using socket programming.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Many websites have large collections of pages generated dynamically from an underlying structured source, like a database.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Data of the same category are typically encoded into similar pages by a common script or template.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] In data mining, a program that detects such templates in a particular information source, extracts its content, and translates it into a relational form, is called a wrapper.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Wrapper generation algorithms assume that input pages of a wrapper induction system conform to a common template and that they can be easily identified in terms of a URL common scheme.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Moreover, some semi-structured data query languages, such as XQuery and the HTQL, can be used to parse HTML pages and to retrieve and transform page content.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] By using a program such as Selenium or Playwright, developers can control a web browser such as Chrome or Firefox to load, navigate, and retrieve data from websites.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] This method can be especially useful for scraping data from dynamic sites since a web browser will fully load each page.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Once an entire page is loaded, developers can access and parse the DOM using an expression language such as XPath.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] There are several companies that have developed vertical specific harvesting platforms.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] These platforms create and monitor a multitude of "bots" for specific verticals with no "man in the loop" (no direct human involvement), and no work related to a specific target site.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] The preparation involves establishing the knowledge base for the entire vertical and then the platform creates the bots automatically.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] The platform's robustness is measured by the quality of the information it retrieves (usually number of fields) and its scalability (how quick it can scale up to hundreds or thousands of sites).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] This scalability is mostly used to target the Long Tail of sites that common aggregators find complicated or too labor-intensive to harvest content from.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] The pages being scraped may embrace metadata or semantic markups and annotations, which can be used to locate specific data snippets.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] If the annotations are embedded in the pages, as Microformat does, this technique can be viewed as a special case of DOM parsing.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] In another case, the annotations, organized into a semantic layer, are stored and managed separately from the web pages, so the scrapers can retrieve data schema and instructions from this layer before scraping the pages.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] There are efforts using machine learning and computer vision that attempt to identify and extract information from web pages by interpreting pages visually as a human being might.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] The legality of web scraping varies across the world.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] In general, web scraping may be against the terms of service of some websites, but the enforceability of these terms is unclear.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] In the United States, website owners can use three major legal claims to prevent undesired web scraping: (1) copyright infringement (compilation), (2) violation of the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act ("CFAA"), and (3) trespass to chattel.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] However, the effectiveness of these claims relies upon meeting various criteria, and the case law is still evolving.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] For example, with regard to copyright, while outright duplication of original expression will in many cases be illegal, in the United States the courts ruled in *Feist Publications v.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Rural Telephone Service* that duplication of facts is allowable.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] U.S. courts have acknowledged that users of "scrapers" or "robots" may be held liable for committing trespass to chattels, which involves a computer system itself being considered personal property upon which the user of a scraper is trespassing.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Bidder's Edge*, resulted in an injunction ordering Bidder's Edge to stop accessing, collecting, and indexing auctions from the eBay web site.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] This case involved automatic placing of bids, known as auction sniping.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Not all cases of web spidering brought before the courts have been considered trespass to chattels.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] One of the first major tests of screen scraping involved American Airlines (AA), and a firm called FareChase.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] AA successfully obtained an injunction from a Texas trial court, stopping FareChase from selling software that enables users to compare online fares if the software also searches AA's website.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] The airline argued that FareChase's websearch software trespassed on AA's servers when it collected the publicly available data.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] FareChase filed an appeal in March 2003.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] By June, FareChase and AA agreed to settle and the appeal was dropped.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Southwest Airlines has also challenged screen-scraping practices, and has involved both FareChase and another firm, Outtask, in a legal claim.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Southwest Airlines charged that the screen-scraping is Illegal since it is an example of "Computer Fraud and Abuse" and has led to "Damage and Loss" and "Unauthorized Access" of Southwest's site.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] It also constitutes "Interference with Business Relations", "Trespass", and "Harmful Access by Computer".
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] They also claimed that screen-scraping constitutes what is legally known as "Misappropriation and Unjust Enrichment", as well as being a breach of the web site's user agreement.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Outtask denied all these claims, claiming that the prevailing law, in this case, should be US Copyright law and that under copyright, the pieces of information being scraped would not be subject to copyright protection.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Although the cases were never resolved in the Supreme Court of the United States, FareChase was eventually shuttered by parent company Yahoo!, and Outtask was purchased by travel expense company Concur.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] In 2012, a startup called 3Taps scraped classified housing ads from Craigslist.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Craigslist sent 3Taps a cease-and-desist letter and blocked their IP addresses and later sued, in *Craigslist v.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] The court held that the cease-and-desist letter and IP blocking was sufficient for Craigslist to properly claim that 3Taps had violated the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act (CFAA).
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Although these are early scraping decisions, and the theories of liability are not uniform, it is difficult to ignore a pattern emerging that the courts are prepared to protect proprietary content on commercial sites from uses which are undesirable to the owners of such sites.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] While the law in this area becomes more settled, entities contemplating using scraping programs to access a public web site should also consider whether such action is authorized by reviewing the terms of use and other terms or notices posted on or made available through the site.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Eventbrite Inc.* (2010), the United States district court for the eastern district of Virginia, ruled that the terms of use should be brought to the users' attention in order for a browsewrap contract or license to be enforceable.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] In a 2014 case, filed in the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania, e-commerce site QVC objected to the Pinterest-like shopping aggregator Resultly's 'scraping of QVC's site for real-time pricing data.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] QVC alleges that Resultly "excessively crawled" QVC's retail site (allegedly sending 200-300 search requests to QVC's website per minute, sometimes to up to 36,000 requests per minute) which caused QVC's site to crash for two days, resulting in lost sales for QVC.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] QVC's complaint alleges that the defendant disguised its web crawler to mask its source IP address and thus prevented QVC from quickly repairing the problem.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] This is a particularly interesting scraping case because QVC is seeking damages for the unavailability of their website, which QVC claims was caused by Resultly.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] In the plaintiff's web site during the period of this trial, the terms of use link are displayed among all the links of the site, at the bottom of the page as most sites on the internet.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] This ruling contradicts the Irish ruling described below.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] The court also rejected the plaintiff's argument that the browse-wrap restrictions were enforceable in view of Virginia's adoption of the Uniform Computer Information Transactions Act (UCITA)—a uniform law that many believed was in favor on common browse-wrap contracting practices.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Power Ventures, Inc.*, a district court ruled in 2012 that Power Ventures could not scrape Facebook pages on behalf of a Facebook user.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] The case is on appeal, and the Electronic Frontier Foundation filed a brief in 2015 asking that it be overturned.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Holdings, Inc.*, a court in the US held Meltwater liable for scraping and republishing news information from the Associated Press, but a court in the United Kingdom held in favor of Meltwater.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] The Ninth Circuit ruled in 2019 that web scraping did not violate the CFAA in *hiQ Labs v.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] The case was appealed to the United States Supreme Court, which returned the case to the Ninth Circuit to reconsider the case in light of the 2021 Supreme Court decision in *Van Buren v.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] United States* which narrowed the applicability of the CFAA.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] On this review, the Ninth Circuit upheld their prior decision.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Internet Archive collects and distributes a significant number of publicly available web pages without being considered to be in violation of copyright laws.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] In February 2006, the Danish Maritime and Commercial Court (Copenhagen) ruled that systematic crawling, indexing, and deep linking by portal site ofir.dk of real estate site Home.dk does not conflict with Danish law or the database directive of the European Union.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Ethical data scraping supports offmarket sourcing in business but must comply with GDPR to avoid privacy violations in automated data collection.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] In a February 2010 case complicated by matters of jurisdiction, Ireland's High Court delivered a verdict that illustrates the inchoate state of developing case law.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] In the case of *Ryanair Ltd v Billigfluege.de GmbH*, Ireland's High Court ruled Ryanair's "click-wrap" agreement to be legally binding.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] The decision is under appeal in Ireland's Supreme Court.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] On April 30, 2020, the French Data Protection Authority (CNIL) released new guidelines on web scraping.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] The CNIL guidelines made it clear that publicly available data is still personal data and cannot be repurposed without the knowledge of the person to whom that data belongs.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] In Australia, the Spam Act 2003 outlaws some forms of web harvesting, although this only applies to email addresses.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] Besides a few cases dealing with IPR infringement, Indian courts have not expressly ruled on the legality of web scraping.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] However, since all common forms of electronic contracts are enforceable in India, violating the terms of use prohibiting data scraping will be a violation of the contract law.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] It will also violate the Information Technology Act, 2000, which penalizes unauthorized access to a computer resource or extracting data from a computer resource.
[src:beautifulsoup-parsing/web-scraping] The administrator of a website can use various measures to stop or slow a bot.
